/**
 * Some of the useful git commands which are used in day to day life
 */

//Some of the useful git commands which are used in day to day life

    git init                        to initialize a git repository
    git add .                       to add all files to staging
    git commit -m "message"         to commit changes to local repo
    git push origin branchname      to push changes to remote repo
    git pull origin branchname      to pull changes from remote repo
    git checkout branchname         to switch to a branch
    git checkout -b branchname      to create a new branch and switch to it
    git branch -d branchname        to delete a branch
    git branch -D branchname        to force delete a branch
    git merge branchname            to merge a branch to current branch
    git log                         to view commit history
    git log --oneline               to view commit history in one line
    git log --oneline --graph        to view commit history in one line with graph
    git log --oneline --graph --decorate   to view commit history in one line with graph and branch names
    git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all   to view commit history in one line with graph and branch names and all branches
    git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all -n 3   to view commit history in one line with graph and branch names and all branches and last 3 commits
    git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all -n 3 --author="name"   to view commit history in one line with graph and branch names and all branches and last 3 commits by a specific author



 1. When creating a new repository
  --------------------- or create a new repository on the command line
 echo "# playwright-typescript-framework" >> README.md
 git init
 git add README.md
 git commit -m "first commit"
 git branch -M main
 git remote add origin <url>
 git push -u origin main

 ===================================================================================
 2. When pushing current repo to remote
 -------- or push an existing repository from the command line
 git remote add origin <url>
 git branch -M main
 git push -u origin main


 ===================================================================================

 3.  Making new branch and pushing to remote
 git checkout master
 git pull origin master
 git checkout -b branchname

 add your changes to staging and commit
 git add .
 git commit -m "message"

 once done push your changes to remote repo
 git push origin branchname


 ---- to switch from one branch to another -----
 	git switch branchname


 ===================================================================================


 4. Remove git tracking from local repo

 $ rm -fr .git


 5. To change or check username and email configured with git

 $ git config user.name "name"

 $ git config user.email "email"


